<section xml:id="sec-measure-1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Starting Measure Theory</title>

  <p> Suppose we want to define a function <m>\lambda(A)</m> to represent the length of the
  real subset <m>A\subset\mathbb{R}</m>. We intuitively expect <m>\lambda</m> to satisfy the following properties:</p>
  <p>
    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li>
        <p><m>\lambda(A)</m> is defined for any <m>A\subset\mathbb{R}</m></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><m>\lambda((a,b])=b-a</m> for any <m>a,b\in\mathbb{R}</m> where <m>a\lt b</m></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><m>0\leq\lambda(A)\leq\infty</m> for any <m>A\subset\mathbb{R}</m></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><m>\lambda(\cup_{i=1}^\infty A_i) = \sum_{i=1}^\infty \lambda(A_i)</m> 
          for any collection <m>\{A_i : i\in\mathbb{N}\}</m> of pairwise disjoint sets</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><m>\lambda(A+x) = \lambda(A+x)</m> is defined for any <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m></p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>

</section>